I and always returns sample products, which may mislead future maintainers.\n- **Readability:** Code is well-structured and readable. Good use of comments (though some are in Chinese).\n- **Efficiency:** No performance issues, but for large datasets, consider using streams or pagination in a real-world scenario.\n- **Edge Cases:** Input parameters are not validated (e.g., null/empty `storeCode`, invalid `orderType`). In a production environment, parameter validation and error handling should be implemented.\n- **Best Practices:** \n    - The `Product` class could include getters and override `equals`/`hashCode` for better usage in collections and future extensibility.\n    - Consider separating concerns: The demo, service, and data entity could be put in distinct files/packages.\n    - Using `List.of()` is fine for demo but should be replaced by dynamic results for real implementation.\n    - Java class and method comments should be in English if the codebase is multilingual.\n    - The `Product` fields can be marked `final` if they are immutable (no setters provided).\n- **Other Suggestions:** If the real API may be asynchronous or network-failure-prone, plan for exceptions and potentially return `Optional<List<Product>>` or throw checked exceptions from `queryMeals`.\n\n**Summary:** This is a solid illustrative/demo code, but for production, add input validation, error handling, proper API integration, and consider maintainability enhancements.","```java\nimport java.util.List;\nimport java.util.Objects;\nimport java.util.Optional;\n\n/**\n * Demo for querying and displaying the McDonald's product list.\n */\npublic class McDonaldsProductListDemo {\n\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        McDonaldsService service = new McDonaldsService();\n\n        // Example parameters: storeCode=\"1001\", orderType=1 (self pickup), no beCode needed.\n        String storeCode = \"1001\";\n        int orderType = 1;\n\n        try {\n            Optional<List<Product>> productListOpt = service.queryMeals(null, orderType, storeCode);\n\n            if (productListOpt.isPresent() && !productListOpt.get().isEmpty()) {\n                System.out.println(\"McDonald's Product List:\");\n                for (Product product : productListOpt.get()) {\n                    System.out.println(product);\n                }\n            } else {\n                System.out.println(\"No product information found.\");\n            }\n        } catch (IllegalArgumentException e) {\n            System.err.println(\"Parameter error: \" + e.getMessage());\n        } catch (Exception e) {\n            System.err.println(\"Failed to retrieve product information: \" + e.getMessage());\n        }\n    }\n}\n\n/**\n * Service class for querying McDonald's products.\n */\nclass McDonaldsService {\n\n    /**\n     * Query product list.\n     *\n     * @param beCode    For delivery scenario, can be passed; null for self-pickup.\n     * @param orderType 1-self pickup, 2-delivery.\n     * @param storeCode Store code, required.\n     * @return Optional product list. In production, should call actual API.\n     * @throws IllegalArgumentException if input parameters are invalid\n     */\n    public Optional<List<Product>> queryMeals(String beCode, int orderType, String storeCode) {\n        // Validate parameters\n        if (storeCode == null || storeCode.trim().isEmpty()) {\n            throw new IllegalArgumentException(\"storeCode cannot be null or empty.\");\n        }\n        if (orderType != 1 && orderType != 2) {\n            throw new IllegalArgumentException(\"orderType must be 1 (self pickup) or 2 (delivery).\");\n        }\n        // In a real implementation, you would call an external API here.\n        // The following is dummy data for demonstration only.\n        List<Product> products = List.of(\n                new Product(\"001\", \"Big Mac\", 25.00),\n                new Product(\"002\", \"Spicy Chicken Burger\", 22.50),\n                new Product(\"003\", \"Medium Fries\", 10.00)\n        );\n        return Optional.of(products);\n    }\n}\n\n/**\n * Product entity for McDonald's menu item.\n */\nclass Product {\n    private final String code;\n    private final String name;\n    private final double price;\n\n    public Product(String code, String name, double price) {\n        this.code = Objects.requireNonNull(code, \"code must not be null\");\n        this.name = Objects.requireNonNull(name, \"name must not be null\");\n        this.price = price;\n    }\n\n    public String getCode() {\n        return code;\n    }\n\n    public String getName() {\n        return name;\n    }\n\n    public double getPrice() {\n        return price;\n    }\n\n    @Override\n    public String toString() {\n        return String.format(\"Product Code: %s, Name: %s, Price: %.2f RMB\", code, name, price);\n    }\n\n    @Override\n    public boolean equals(Object o) {\n        if (this == o) return true;\n        if (!(o instanceof Product)) return false;\n        Product product = (Product) o;\n        return Double.compare(product.price, price) == 0 &&\n                code.equals(product.code) &&\n                name.equals(product.name);\n    }\n\n    @Override\n    public int hashCode() {\n        return Objects.hash(code, name, price);\n    }\n}\n```\n"]
